  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-6 mt-10">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="space-y-3 not-prose">
    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
      <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
        What clearances are required around a disc stack centrifuge?
        <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
      </summary>
      <p class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">Disc stack centrifuges require a minimum of 36 inches clearance on the service side (for bowl removal) and 24 inches on other sides. Overhead clearance must accommodate bowl lift during service — typically 4–6 feet above the bowl top. Always consult the specific centrifuge model's installation manual for exact clearance requirements.</p>
    </details>
    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
      <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
        Does a disc stack centrifuge require a special foundation?
        <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
      </summary>
      <p class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">Most disc stack centrifuges can be installed on a standard reinforced concrete floor rated for the centrifuge weight plus dynamic loads. Anti-vibration mounts are recommended to isolate normal operating vibration from the building structure. Some larger models may require anchor bolts into the floor. The floor must be level to within 2mm across the centrifuge base frame.</p>
    </details>
    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
      <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
        What utilities does a disc stack centrifuge require?
        <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
      </summary>
      <p class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">A disc stack centrifuge typically requires: (1) Electrical power — 230/460 VAC three-phase for the main motor; (2) Operating water — clean water at 10–15 PSI for bowl ejection cycles; (3) Compressed air — 80–100 PSI for pneumatically operated valves (if equipped); (4) Steam or hot water for feed preheating (if heaters are not electric).</p>
    </details>
    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
      <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
        Can a disc stack centrifuge be installed outdoors?
        <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
      </summary>
      <p class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">Standard disc stack centrifuges are not designed for outdoor installation — they require shelter from rain, direct sunlight, and freezing temperatures. For outdoor or remote applications, a weatherproof enclosure or containerized centrifuge system (ISO container) provides the necessary protection. Explosion-proof models can be specified for outdoor hazardous area locations.</p>
    </details>
    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
      <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
        How should feed and discharge tanks be positioned relative to the centrifuge?
        <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
      </summary>
      <p class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">The feed tank should ideally be positioned above the centrifuge feed pump to provide positive suction head. The clean oil discharge tank should be at or below the centrifuge discharge level to avoid back pressure from static head. Sludge and water discharge lines should drain by gravity to collection tanks — avoid any upward runs that create back pressure on centrifuge discharge ports.</p>
    </details>
  </div>

